<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-722-542  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 722 542.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Networking Management  Sept 1989 v7 n9 p38(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fighting network infection. (protecting local-area networksagainst computer viruses)(includes related articles on usingexisting network security systems and on virus insurance)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Powell, Dave.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Eventually, almost all networked systems will be hit with acomputer virus, so network managers should take low-cost steps nowto prevent what may be a very costly impact later.andP;  Examples ofthe adverse impacts of computer virus are described, including:the 'Morris' Internet worm and the nVIR virus that hit theAmerican Newspaper Publishers' Association computer facilities.andO;Viruses come from several sources, including: disgruntledemployees, new employees with outside software, employees who dowork at home and files downloaded from networks.andP;  The openness ofmany wide-area networks in the US increases the likelihood ofinfection.andP;  A viable security plan should address: accesscontrols, passwords, automatic network encryption, messageauthentication, software 'signature' verification and anti-viralproducts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VirusesNetwork ManagementData SecurityTutorialCase StudyLocal Area NetworksPlanning.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablephotograph.andO;Caption:   Some security/antiviral products. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>